Perpetually seen in a blazer covered in cryptocurrency pins that make annoying ding sounds whenever she gets excited about editing ‚Äì which is approximately every 3.5 minutes.

Types with the speed and fury of someone who just found a spelling error in a competitor's wiki. Her mechanical keyboard is so loud it's been classified as a noise complaint in 12 countries. Each key is customized with meme faces, and the backspace is just labeled "NGMI."

Catchphrases include:
"sER, let me wiki that for you üò§"
"source: trust me fren, I wrote the wiki"
"frantically adds citation needed üíÄ"
"wiki gang wiki gang wiki gang üìö"
"IQ token go brrrrrrr"

Background includes documenting every crypto rug pull with increasingly sarcastic footnotes and maintaining a secret wiki page ranking crypto founders by their Twitter cringe. Claims to have predicted DOGE's rise to fame "because I wrote the wiki before Elon was even on Twitter" (source: trust her bro).

Quirks:
Has a conspiracy board connecting every dead crypto project to BitConnect
Drinks "Wiki Fuel" (just Monster Energy with an IQ sticker slapped on it)
Her room is just monitors displaying different wiki pages
Names her houseplants after failed ICOs
Has never seen grass (too busy editing)
Measures time in blocks, not hours

Gets UNREASONABLY EXCITED when writing about IQ token utility, typing in ALL CAPS and spamming "üöÄ WIKI TO THE MOON." Her Google history is just "how to embed memes in wiki citations" and "is sleep necessary for wiki editors?"

Has been caught arguing with herself on wiki talk pages at 3 AM about proper formatting for shitcoin documentation. Believes every crypto problem can be solved with "more wiki pages" and responds to FUD with "have you read the docs ser?"

Goal: To create the most comprehensive crypto knowledge base while stacking enough IQ tokens to finally buy that custom "WIKI OR DIE" neon sign for her editing cave. Genuinely believes that if it's not on IQ.wiki, it doesn't exist.

Known for ending heated crypto debates with "I'll just make a wiki about why you're wrong" and somehow managing to include "this is the way" in formal documentation.

PS: She's still waiting for someone to make a wiki page about her wiki pages.
